<article id="post-2256" class="hentry post publish post-1 odd author-admin format-standard category-review">

	
		
		<header class="entry-header">
			<h1 class="post-title entry-title"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071442/http://novelideareviews.com/author-interview-giveaway-ak-host/">Author Interview + Giveaway: AK Höst</a></h1>			<div class="byline">Published by <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" rel="author" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071442/http://novelideareviews.com/author/admin/" title="Paola">Paola</a></span> on <abbr class="published" title="Friday, June 14th, 2013, 8:00 am">June 14, 2013</abbr>  | <a class="comments-link" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071442/http://novelideareviews.com/author-interview-giveaway-ak-host/#comments" title="Comment on Author Interview + Giveaway: AK Höst">14 Responses</a> </div>		</header><!-- .entry-header -->
		
		<div class="entry-content">
			<p><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071442/http://nuzsaysitwithbooks.blogspot.com/" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push(['_trackEvent','outbound-article','https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071442/http://nuzsaysitwithbooks.blogspot.com']);" target="_blank"><img class="aligncenter" alt="indieeventbanner" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071442im_/http://novelideareviews.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/indieeventbanner.png" width="416" height="70"/></a></p>
<h4 style="text-align: justify;">I&#8217;m extremely excited to spotlight one of my favorite authors this week as part of the <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071442/http://nuzsaysitwithbooks.blogspot.com/" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push(['_trackEvent','outbound-article','https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071442/http://nuzsaysitwithbooks.blogspot.com']);" target="_blank">Indie &amp; Self-Published Author Event</a>: the awesome A.K. Höst! Be sure to check out my reviews of <a title="And All the Stars" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071442/http://novelideareviews.com/and-all-the-stars/" target="_blank"><em>And All the Stars</em></a> (if you&#8217;re looking for some great sci-fi) and <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071442/http://novelideareviews.com/hunting/" target="_blank"><em>Hunting</em></a> (if you&#8217;re in the mood for some fantasy), and you can learn more about the author on <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071442/http://andreakhost.com/" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push(['_trackEvent','outbound-article','https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071442/http://andreakhost.com']);" target="_blank">her blog</a> too!</h4>
<h4 style="text-align: justify;">Today I&#8217;m over the moon because I get to post this awesome <strong>interview</strong> as well as <strong>a reader&#8217;s choice giveaway</strong>!</h4>
<h3 style="text-align: center;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">An Interview with Andrea K. Höst</span></h3>
<h4>- I think your books feature some very strong heroines, which is one big reason why I love them so much. Which heroines in fiction are your favorites or are the most inspiring to you, and why?</h4>
<p style="text-align: justify;">My favourite heroines tend to be the practical ones.  Who figure out ways to get around hurdles.  They don&#8217;t necessarily have to be the smartest, or the fastest, or the cleverest or the prettiest, or even to succeed nine times out of ten &#8211; but they work best for me if they&#8217;re sensible.  I also like them wry or sarcastic, and generous of spirit.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">I think Sophie Hatter from &#8220;Howl&#8217;s Moving Castle&#8221; is one of my favourites.  Sophie underestimates herself &#8211; she thinks she&#8217;s fated to fail, but she doesn&#8217;t allow resentment to colour her relationship with her prettier/more-fortunate sisters.  When she&#8217;s transformed, she gets a bit flustered, but she adjusts to her situation and starts looking for ways to cope.  She starts to stand up for herself, and doesn&#8217;t back down when it&#8217;s important.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span id="more-2256"></span></p>
<h4>- Since you mentioned Sophie from Howl&#8217;s Moving Castle, I&#8217;m now curious &#8212; have you seen the film adaptation? If so, what did you think? (I happen to be a huge fan of Sophie as well!)</h4>
<p style="text-align: justify;">I really enjoyed it.  I&#8217;d read and loved the book long before I saw the movie, and naturally there were a lot of things the movie changed, but it was still a beautiful movie, and caught the magic of the tale, if not the details.  It&#8217;s one of a small handful of movies I own on DVD and I re-watch it occasionally &#8211; though I think I re-read the book a little more often.</p>
<h4>- What qualities do you think a &#8220;strong heroine&#8221; should have? What does that role mean to you?</h4>
<p style="text-align: justify;">I have a love of stories of &#8220;girls doing stuff&#8221;.  Or &#8220;women getting stuff done&#8221;.  A heroine is a fairly broad word, and can cover all types of women.  A heroine might be brash, she might be shy, she might be able to level mountains, she might have little ability to defend herself, she might skin rabbits, she might love dress-up, she might be a coward, or even a little bit cruel.  But she is willing to make a stand or take risks for the things which are important to her &#8211; someone who acts when it is absolutely necessary.  I don&#8217;t have a great deal of tolerance for characters who don&#8217;t even try to help.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">This is in addition to &#8220;strongly-written&#8221; or &#8220;not a paper-thin cipher&#8221; (which is what I think of when someone talks about &#8220;strong female characters&#8221; as opposed to &#8220;strong heroine&#8221;). In other words, someone who seems rounded and real.</p>
<h4>- I&#8217;ve read about your experience with trying to get published traditionally and why it brought you down the self-pub route. What would you say is the best thing about self-pub vs. traditional?</h4>
<p style="text-align: justify;">The control.  Not having my ability to bring my stories to readers locked away behind a gate.  I never want to sent in a submission again &#8211; it&#8217;s such a negative part of the publishing process.</p>
<h4>- Which of your characters would have the easiest time getting along with?</h4>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Oh, a toughie.  I suspect I&#8217;d find a lot of my characters intimidating.  I think I&#8217;d really like Ketzaren from First Squad in the Touchstone Trilogy.  I like the dry, sarcastic people.</p>
<h4>- Conversely, whose personality would probably clash with yours?</h4>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Well, I doubt I&#8217;d like Kajal or Forel from &#8220;The Touchstone Trilogy&#8221;. Of the main characters, I suspect Strake from &#8220;Champion of the Rose&#8221; would be difficult to deal with.  He does try hard to control his temper, but it would still take a lot of energy to deal with him.</p>
<h4>- Have any of your characters surprised you or taken a different path than what you intended while writing?</h4>
<p style="text-align: justify;">One of my villains decided she was far better than I&#8217;d thought her, and refused to be behind all the evil machinations.  I had to go back and insert a new character into that book just to have someone to blame.</p>
<h4>- How much of your own personality finds its way into the characters you write?</h4>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Bits and pieces.  I&#8217;ve never written a character that felt like &#8220;me&#8221;, but they will quite often hold suspiciously similar opinions on certain matters.  And sometimes they&#8217;ll be quite different &#8211; Cass Devlin, for instance, went through a patch of enjoying drinking and smoking, and I&#8217;ve never liked either.</p>
<h4>- I love how immersive and detailed your fantasy worlds are; it&#8217;s definitely one of my favorite things about your writing. Do you have a process for world building, or do you allow the settings of your stories to develop organically as you write? I know you state on your blog that you&#8217;re not an outliner but I wondered if this applies to creating the setting as well.</h4>
<p style="text-align: justify;">I&#8217;m definitely a discovery writer where it comes to the world, as well.  Though there are a lot of shades in between &#8220;making it up on the fly&#8221; and &#8220;writing an outline&#8221; first.  I usually start with a scene or an idea, write the first chapter or two, and by the time I&#8217;m done with that I have a very good idea of where the story is heading, and know a fair bit about the world &#8211; which becomes more detailed the longer I write.  The story I&#8217;m writing at the moment ,&#8221;The Pyramids of London&#8221;, is set in an alternate version of our world, and I have four support documents &#8211; a map, a glossary, a character list and a timeline, and as I write further into the novel, I add details and events to the support documents  to keep track of things I&#8217;ve &#8216;discovered&#8217; or decided about the world.  Because it&#8217;s alt-Earth there&#8217;s a lot of detail to keep track of.</p>
<h4>- Do you have any advice for aspiring writers out there?</h4>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Read a lot.  Write a lot.  Learn what the rules are, and then write the way you want to.  Learn to distinguish between what people say are rules, and what are really myths and conformity.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"> And write because you love it.</p>
<h4 style="text-align: justify;"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071442/http://novelideareviews.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/AKHOST_giveaway.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-2321" alt="AKHOST_giveaway" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071442im_/http://novelideareviews.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/AKHOST_giveaway.png" width="566" height="263"/></a>Enter for a chance to win an e-book copy of your choice, courtesy of the author, who is very generously offering any of her books up for grabs! This is open internationally. And please be sure to read <a title="Giveaway Policy" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071442/http://novelideareviews.com/giveaway-policy/"><strong>our giveaway policy</strong></a>!</h4>
